Wash and dry all produce. Halve and peel @red onion{1}. Thinly slice one half; finely
dice other half until you have ¼ cup diced onion. Quarter @heirloom grape tomatoes{8%oz}.
Zest @lime{1} until you have 1 tsp zest, then cut into halves. Core and seed @bell pepper{2},
then thinly slice. Chop @cilantro{½%oz}.

In a #small bowl{}, toss together diced onion, tomatoes, lime zest, a squeeze of lime juice,
and half the cilantro. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Set aside until meal is ready.

> TIP: If you don't have a microwave to use in step 5, now is a good time to preheat your
> oven to 425 degrees.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add
sliced onion and bell peppers. Cook until softened and slightly blistered, ~{4-5%minutes},
tossing occasionally. Season with salt and pepper.

Cut @pork chops{24%oz} into thin strips, slicing against the grain. Season with salt and
pepper. When veggies are done, remove from pan and set aside. Heat another large drizzle of
@vegetable oil{2%tsp} in same pan over medium-high heat. Add as much pork as will fit without
crowding (you may need to work in batches). Cook, tossing occasionally, until browned all
over and nearly cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes} per batch.

Return veggies and all pork to pan along with @Southwest spice blend{2%tbsp} and a squeeze
of lime juice. Cook, tossing, until pork is no longer pink in center, ~{2-3%minutes}. Meanwhile,
wrap @flour tortillas{12} in a damp #paper towel{} and microwave on high until warm, about
~{30%seconds}.

> TIP: Alternatively, wrap tortillas in foil and warm in oven for 5 minutes at 425 degrees.

When everything is ready, set up a station for the fajitas: place salsa, filling,
tortillas, @sour cream{8%tbsp}, @cheddar cheese{1%cup}, and remaining cilantro in individual
plates or #bowls{} and invite everyone to assemble their own fajitas.